Uses of Interface
teal.math.Integratable

  • Packages that use Integratable 
    Package Description
    teal.math
    Provides the integration model and the generalized classes for performing different integration schemes, and also defines special functions, for example elliptical integrals, and also defines geometry objects, for example planes using the Point Normal form.
    teal.physics
    Physics properties and objects that may be added to the world.
    teal.physics.em
    Provides classes and interfaces for adding electromagnetic objects to the world.
    teal.physics.mech
    Provides mechanical (kinematic) objects that can be added to the world.
    teal.physics.physical
    Physical objects that may be added to the world.
    teal.sim.engine
    Provides class that define and support the TEALsim simulation engine (SimEngine).
    teal.sim.properties
    Provides interfaces for Simulation objects physical and EM properties.

      Modifier and Type Interface and Description
      interface  MetaIntegratable
      This interface extends Integratable, and should be implemented by those TealObjects that need to be integrated, but might have internal variables that are interdependent.
      Methods in teal.math with parameters of type Integratable 
      Modifier and Type Method and Description
      static double[] RungeKutta4.integrate(Integratable rk, double s_start, double stepsize)
      Given a Integratable object, this method computes new values for all of the dependent variables passed in.
      static double[] RungeKutta4.integrate(Integratable rk, double s_start, double stepsize, double eps)
      Starting at s1, this method returns an estimate of X at s2 with a specified error.
      private static double[] RungeKutta4.rungeKuttaFourthOrder(Integratable rk, double[] X_at_s, double[] dXds_at_s, double s_start, double h)
      This is the basic fourth order RungeKutta stepping routine.
      private static double[] RungeKutta4.rungeKuttaQualityControl(Integratable rk, double[] Xnew, double[] dXds, double sgiven, double htry, double eps, double[] Xscal)
      Given a value of X and dX/ds at s, a stepsize h, an allowed error, and a way to compute dX/ds at new points, this method will return a new value of the dependent variables X at s, where s incremented over s by an amount not more than h, but perhaps much less than h, but with an error in X of less than the desired error.
